{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643119"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:51:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:51:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17989"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17989"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79248"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10703"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17989"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64590"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24921"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79248","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79248"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring intense physical exercise, skeletal muscle cells experience significant changes in their energy status. These changes affect various cellular signalling pathways that regulate metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following changes in nucleotide concentrations is most likely to activate adenosine monophosphate-activated protein kinase in skeletal muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased ATP, decreased AMP","Increased ATP, decreased AMP","Increased ATP, increased AMP","Decreased ATP, increased AMP","Increased ATP, unchanged AMP"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased ATP, increased AMP\u003C/strong\u003E is the condition most likely to activate AMPK. During high-intensity exercise, the demand for ATP in muscle cells increases significantly. As ATP is consumed, the levels of AMP rise, leading to an increased AMP/ATP ratio. This change in the ratio signals low energy status within the cell, triggering the activation of AMPK.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased ATP, decreased AMP\u003C/strong\u003E would not activate AMPK, as a decrease in both ATP and AMP does not reflect the typical energy-depleted state that triggers AMPK activation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased ATP, decreased AMP\u003C/strong\u003E indicates a high energy state, which does not activate AMPK\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased ATP, increased AMP\u003C/strong\u003E is physiologically unlikely as ATP and AMP levels typically have an inverse relationship during energy consumption\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased ATP, unchanged AMP\u003C/strong\u003E would not activate AMPK as this indicates sufficient cellular energy\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce activated, AMPK promotes catabolic processes that generate ATP while inhibiting anabolic processes that consume ATP, helping to restore cellular energy balance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Adenosine monophosphate-activated protein kinase (AMPK) is activated in response to low energy states within the cell.","AMPK activation occurs when there is an increase in the AMP/ATP ratio, indicating a depletion of cellular energy.","AMPK plays a crucial role in cellular energy homeostasis by promoting catabolic pathways that generate ATP."],"references":["Gilbert-Barness, E., Barness, L. A., \u0026 Farrell, P. M. (Eds.). (2017). Metabolic diseases: foundations of clinical management, genetics, and pathology. IOS Press","Lanham-New, S. A., Macdonald, I. A., \u0026 Roche, H. M. (Eds.). (2011). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Roche, H. M., Macdonald, I. A., Schols, A. M., \u0026 Lanham-New, S. A. (Eds.). (2024). Nutrition and metabolism. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Omiecinski CJ, Vanden Heuvel JP, Perdew GH, Peters JM. Xenobiotic metabolism, disposition, and regulation by receptors: from biochemical phenomenon to predictors of major toxicities. Toxicol Sci. 2011 Mar;120 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):S49-75. doi: 10.1093/toxsci/kfq338. Epub 2010 Nov 8. PMID: 21059794; PMCID: PMC3145385","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64590"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17989"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64590"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T21:11:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T21:12:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10703"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79248"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relation